Painter does for racial history what Thomas Sowell did for political philosophy in his volume A Conflict of Visions.
She refers to him as the “philosopher king of American white race theory.” She contends that he wrote one of the earliest and most-complete statements of a belief system that would later be referred to as Anglo-Saxonism.
This way of thinking had recently been accepted by Catholic Irish and Germans who had finally become “old” immigrants during the Second Enlargement of American Whiteness.
She accepted as a given that Nordics, Alpines, and Mediterraneans existed, and that the Nordics were the white race.
We can appreciate the work Margaret Sanger did—who is conspicuously absent from History of White People—through her founding of Planned Parenthood, despite her advocacy of eugenics.